<1ST_LINE>r w BC-SocialSecurity-Figures     08-05 0356</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Social Security-Figures,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With PM-Social Security</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is an example of the information the
Social Security Administration will provide in its new ``Personal
Earnings and Benefit Estimate Statement.''
   The figures are actual estimates for a 40-year-old ``John Q.
Public'' based on a history of moderate wages for the past two
decades.
   This person, born Dec. 16, 1947, must wait until 66 to qualify
for full Social Security retirement benefits.
   He told Social Security he earned $23,938 in 1987, expects to
earn $23,000 this year and the equivalent of $23,000 in future
years.
   Social Security reported back that his earnings record showed
nothing earned in 1963 and earlier, and the following in Social
Security-taxed earnings and estimated taxes paid since then:
   1964: $632 $22.
   1965: $497 $18.
   1966: $3,607 $151.
   1967: $4,053 $178.
   1968: $3,833 $168.
   1969: $5,282 $253.
   1970: $6,253 $300.
   1971: $7,142 $371.
   1972: $8,295 $431.
   1973: $9,001 $526.
   1974: $10,239 $599
   1975: $11,163 $653
   1976: $11,516 $673
   1977: $12,663 $740
   1978: $13,769 $833
   1979: $15,158 $929
   1989: $17,407 $1,067
   1981: $18,495 $1,229
   1982: $20,858 $1,397
   1983: $22,485 $1,506
   1984: $25,085 $1,680
   1985: $26,587 $1,874
   1986: $25,647 $1,833
   1987: Not Yet Posted
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Then it provided the following retirement benefit estimates:
   At age 62, a monthly benefit in today's dollars of $730.
   At age 66, $970.
   At age 70, $1,285.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   SURVIVORS:
   A surviving child could get $605 a month.
   If a child and a surviving spouse caring for a child both
qualify, each could get $605.
   The surviving spouse could receive $810 a month when she or her
reaches full retirement age.
   The maximum family benefit would be $1,420 a month.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   DISABILITY:
   This worker's monthly disability check would be $805.
   He and his family could receive up to $1,205 a month.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   The booklet will also explain the payroll tax rates, currently
7.51 percent on employees and employers and 13.02 percent on the
self-employed. The tax pays for both Social Security and Medicare.
   The brochures notes that currently, the average monthly benefit
for a retired worker 65 or older is $523, plus Medicare benefits
valued at $202 a month.
