<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Nicaragua     08-05 0518</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaragua,0532</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ortega Threatens To Hit Opposition If US Renews Contra Aid</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Shultz, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FILADELFO ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel Ortega said the
leftist Sandinista government would crack down harder on the
domestic political opposition if the United States renews
assistance to the Contra rebels.
   Also Thursday, the foreign minister sent U.S. Secretary of State
George P. Shultz a note protesting a river boat ambush that the
government and witnesses blamed on the rebels.
   Shultz is touring Latin America this week and was in Brazil
today. In Uruguay on Thursday, he accused the Soviets of building
airstrips in Nicaragua, and called the Sandinistas a cancer that
the United States must cut out before it spreads.
   Aid to the Contras ran out in February, but Congress is
considering new money for the insurgents the United States has been
financing since 1981.
   The government and the rebels agreed to a cease-fire on March
23, and the government unilaterally extended the truce to the end
of August.
   Speaking at an electricity plant near Momotombo about 45 miles
northwest of Managua, Ortega warned that the government would ``cut
off the oxygen'' of the internal opposition and begin fighting the
Contras again if a U.S. aid package is approved.
   In Washington, the White House on Thursday rejected a $27
million Senate Democratic proposal for humanitarian aid to the
rebels but said Congress and the Reagan administration could still
work out a compromise.
   ``Yankee pressure is not going to make the Sandinistas more
flexible,'' Orega said. ``Yankee pressure is going to toughen the
Sandinistas.''
   The government jailed more than 30 opposition figures and
cracked down on opposition media after police broke up a large
anti-government rally on July 10. It expelled U.S. Ambassador
Richard Melton and seven other American diplomats, and Washington
responded by expelling eight Nicaraguan diplomats.
   In a note dated Wednesday, Foreign Minister Miguel D'Escoto
reminded Shultz that Tuesday's boat attack, which killed two people
and wounded at least 24, was carried out ``a few hours from your
stop in the region.''
   ``Your visit to Central America once again has helped encourage
the war and the state terrorism that your country practices against
Nicaragua, in flagrant violation of the norms and principles of
international law,'' D'Escoto wrote.
   The note was read to The Associated Press by an official at the
Foreign Ministry.
   Radio Liberacion, the rebels' station, blamed the attack on the
Sandinistas. They called it a staged ``attack on themselves''
intended to dissuade the U.S. Congress from approving new aid for
the rebels.
   The Defense Ministry said the boat was hit by rifle and mortar
fire about 150 mile southeast of Managua on the Escondido River, a
major military supply route of the government. About 200
Nicaraguans and 10 Americans were on the boat, and an American, an
Italian and a Costa Rican were among the injured.
   The Rev. Lucius Walker of Demarest, N.J., who was grazed in the
buttocks by a bullet in the attack, said Wednesday the U.S.
government was responsible for terrorism because of its financial
support for the rebels.
</TEXT>
