<DOCNO> AP880805-0012 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-05-88 0232EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel-Economy     08-05 0777</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Economy,0801</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Uprising, Labor Disputes Heat Up Inflation, Slow Growth</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Palestinian uprising, election year
politics and protracted labor disputes are undermining Israel's
economic recovery program by pushing up inflation and reducing
growth.
   Industrial production is down 3.5 percent, the first such drop
in eight years, and inflation is expected to exceed 20 percent, up
from 16 percent last year and a third higher than initially
forecast.
   ``We had to scale down our expectations'' after more optimistic
projections in early 1988, said Ruth Lowental, assistant director
general of economic affairs in the Finance Ministry.
   The gloomier prognosis is accompanied by a ``feeling of
insecurity because nobody knows what's going to happen after the
(Nov. 1 national) election,'' said Joseph Canaan, an Israeli
journalist who writes for two West German economic publications.
   A key reason for the slump is the 8-month-old Arab uprising in
the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip already has eaten up more
than half of this year's growth, initially projected at 3.7 percent.
   The uprising has cost more than $700 million in lost tourism,
uncollected taxes and additional military expenses, said Amnon
Neubach, an economic adviser to Foreign Minister Shimon Peres.
   In addition, fewer of the 1.5 million Palestinians in the
occupied lands buy Israeli products and about 20 percent of the
110,000 Palestinians working in Israel no longer report to their
jobs as a result of a Palestinian boycott.
   ``When you have 1.5 million consumers who used to buy Israeli
products, and they stopped doing it, it has a serious effect,''
said an Israeli industrialist, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Stability is also threatened by increasing wage demands, backed
by numerous strikes by Israeli workers. Excluding Palestinian work
stoppages, the Israeli economy lost 1.3 million work days due to
strikes in 1987, more than triple the 1986 figure.
   The labor disputes indicate workers are no longer willing to
make the kind of sacrifices they accepted during a 1985 austerity
program.
   Workers then accepted wage cuts of up to 20 percent to help stem
soaring inflation and reduce a $3 billion budget deficit.
   The program worked. Inflation dropped to 16.1 percent in 1987,
and the budget deficit fell from 13.6 percent of the Gross Domestic
Product of 1.2 billion shekels in 1984 to a surplus of 1.7 percent
of the 1986 GDP of 1.3 billion shekels ($812 million).
   But in the past two years, real wages have been rising faster
than productivity, heating up inflation. And Finance Minister Moshe
Nissim is under growing pressure to make concessions as the
election campaign is heating up.
   ``Our basic target is to maintain stability,'' Ms. Lowental
said. ``But nobody knows what's going to happen with the wages.''
   Still unsigned is a tentative agreement for an 11 percent wage
increase over two years for the 450,000 civil servants, one-third
of the civilian labor force. Also unresolved are private sector
negotzed
national health system with months of strikes and slowdowns.
   The government agreed to emergency payments to ease the backlog
of 15,000 Israelis waiting for operations, but there has been
little progress in wage talks for doctors who earn an average $700
a month and are seeking wage hikes of more than 20 percent.
   If the doctors get large increases, ``it could affect the whole
wage structure. If you give higher wages to one group of people,
you have to give more to all the others,'' said Canaan.
   Nissim also is under pressure to devalue the Israeli shekel
which has been fixed at a rate of about 1.6 shekels to the dollar
since the days of hyperinflation.
   Manufacturers complain the strong shekel is making it difficult
for Israeli exports to compete and is partly to blame for the drop
in industrial production.
   Nissim has refused to devalue for fear of raising import prices
and fueling inflation.
   Especially hard hit is Koor, the industrial conglomerate of the
powerful Histadrut Trade Union Federation, which lost $250 million
in 1987, a record in Israeli industry.
   The United States, which gives Israel $1.2 billion a year in
economic aid, urged Israel to sell off state-owned companies, lower
taxes and cut government spending.
   The government has taken some steps in that direction. But Chaim
Barkai, economics professor at Hebrew University, said no unpopular
steps would be taken during the three-month election campaign.
   ``The government must close down unprofitable factories and cut
spending. But there won't be any changes in economic policy before
the elections,'' Barkai said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880805-0013 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-05-88 0016EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-UN-Gulf Bjt   08-05 0629</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UN-Gulf, Bjt,0647</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Chief Proposes Compromise In Persian Gulf Standoff</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran and Iraq would simultaneously halt
their bloodshed and begin peace talks under a compromise solution
proposed by the U.N. chief, but sources say Iraq is cool to the
idea.
   Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar received a report
Thursday from a U.N. military team that visited both nations on
arrangements for a U.N.-supervised cease-fire. The contents were
not disclosed, but the U.N. chief said he would make a report to
the Security Council today.
   Perez de Cuellar has been trying to resolve a standoff between
the two nations over the timing of a truce and the start of
cease-fire talks in their 8-year-old war.
   ``I think both parties are interested in a peaceful solution ..
. The concept of direct talks is accepted by both sides and the
matter is when (they will take place). That is something on which I
am working,'' he said Thursday.
   The issue of face-to-face talks between the bitter enemies has
complicated the talks on implementing a truce and a U.N. peace
plan. Iraq demands that direct talks be held before a cease-fire
and Iran says they can begin only after a truce.
   Diplomatic sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
Perez de Cuellar has proposed to both sides that he announce a
cease-fire date and simultaneously invite both sides to hold direct
talks on a comprehensive peace treaty.
   The sources say the talks and a truce could begin the same day,
perhaps in a week if both sides are agreeable.
   Iraq also is asking that the five permanent members of the
Security Council guarantee the truce and other elements of a peace
plan. The five _ United States, Soviet Union, China, Britain and
France _ are considering the issue, the sources said.
   Perez de Cuellar did not spell out his proposals for reporters
and said he has not yet received a formal response from Iraq.
   Diplomatic sources say Baghdad is not enthusiastic about the
idea, but stopped short of outright rejection of the proposed
simultaneous announcement.
   Perez de Cuellar said Iran's response, although not formal, has
been ``constructive.''
   ``Unfortunately, from the Iraqi side, I have not received the
comments which I have asked for,'' Perez de Cuellar told reporters
as he left U.N. headquarters.
   Meanwhile, the official Iraqi News Agency said in a dispatch
from the United Nations that Iraqi Foreign Minister Tariq Aziz, who
heads Iraq's negotiating team, met Thursday with the U.S. envoy to
the U.N., Ambassador Vernon Walters, and visiting Indian Foreign
Minister P.V. Narasimha Rao.
   The agency said the men discussed the cease-fire resolution and
other issues, but gave no other details.
   Perez de Cuellar said that next week, probably Wednesday, he
would deliver a comprehensive report to the council on the
cease-fire declaration, troop withdrawal, prisoner exchange and
other elements of a U.N. peace plan.
   Iran and Iraq have waged war since 1980, when Iraq invaded
Iranian territory. The death toll is estimated at 1 million.
   The Security Council in July 1987 adopted a resolution calling
for a cease-fire in the war, which has prompted an escalated U.S.
naval presence in the gulf.
   Iraq accepted the proposal, but it was not until last month that
Iran, after a series of battlefield defeats, said it, too, would
accept the resolution. Since then, Iraq has launched several
attacks on Iran to bolster its bargaining position.
   Iranian Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati met the U.N. chief
for more than one hour Thursday. The Iranian envoy made no comments
as he left the meeting.
   Iraq says it needs the direct talks as a guarantee of sincerity
from Iran, which it fears will seek only a temporary truce to
regroup forces.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
