<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Unemployment Bjt   08-05 0537</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Unemployment, Bjt,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Economists Expect Unemployment Rate To Stabilize</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Will be topped with release at 8:30 a.m. EDT of figures for
July</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With youths fully absorbed into the summer job
market, economists are looking to the nation's unemployment rate to
stabilize after a couple of months of large fluctuations.
   On the eve of today's release of labor market figures for July,
most economists expected the rate either to remain at its
14-year-low 5.3 percent in June or to rise a tenth of a percentage
point with an employment increase of 150,000 to 200,000.
   The jobless rate had bounced like a roller coaster from 5.6
percent in March, down to 5.4 percent in April and back up to 5.6
percent in May before the June decline.
   Both private analysts and economists for the Bureau of Labor
Statistics said the monthly fluctuations were due primarily to two
factors:
   One factor is the adjustments the government makes with the May
and June figures to account for the out-of-school youths flooding
the job market.
   The other factor is the calendar. The survey of 55,800
households upon which the rate is calculated is always taken on the
12th day of the month. Because the 12th occurred in the second week
of May but the third week in June, economists said the real rate of
joblessness was probably lower than what was reported in May and
higher than the June figure.
   ``I think there will be an uptick to 5.4 percent for July,''
said Allen Sinai, chief economist of The Boston Co. ``But I
wouldn't consider that as indicative of any new trend or a
weakening of the economy.''
   Payroll growth soared in June with 345,000 new jobs, compared
with average monthly increases of 250,000 from January through May.
After slowing down in the spring, factory and construction
employment also resumed their upward paths in June.
   The Labor Department reported Thursday that new claims for
unemployment insurance _ seasonally adjusted _ jumped by 51,000 in
the third week of July to 371,000, the highest since last January.
   ``If the unemployment claims are rising that rapidly, then new
job creation may be a little skinny in July,'' said Michael Evans,
a private Washington economist who also expected the rate of
joblessness to rise to 5.4 percent.
   However, other analysts attributed the increase in applications
for unemployment benefits to temporary layoffs in the auto industry
as manufacturers retooled their assembly lines for the 1989 models.
   Meanwhile, fears that continuous months of unemployment rates in
the range of 5.3 percent to 5.7 percent might trigger wage
inflation so far appear unfounded.
   Although employers in tight job market areas along the East
Coast and in California are finding they have to pay much more than
the minimum wage to attract workers for entry-level jobs, pay
increases in general are still below inflation.
   Hourly wages actually fell 2 cents an hour in June to a
seasonally adjusted $9.27, according to the Labor Department.
   ``Real wage rates have not yet recovered from a decade of price
shocks and slow economic growth,'' said Wendy Rayack, a Wesleyan
University economist. ``They are still nearly 7 percent below their
1978 level.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
