<HEAD>Vassiliou Says Dukakis, Bush Both Would Seek Cyprus Settlement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President George Vassiliou of Cyprus said
Thursday that both U.S. presidential candidates have ``clearly
indicated'' they want to heighten American involvement in seeking
an end to the Greek-Turkish division of his nation.
   ``Both of them (Republican George Bush and Democrat Michael
Dukakis) have shown an increased interest in the Cyprus issue and
have clearly indicated that they would like a more active role
played by the United States,'' Vassiliou said.
   Dukakis' campaign reportedly has received strong financial
support from the Greek-American community which has been calling
for a withdrawal of the Turkish forces which have occupied Cyprus
since 1974.
   Asked whether he thought Dukakis or Bush would play a more
active role in seeking a solution to the Cyprus problem, Vassiliou
noted the strong support he perceived on both sides, saying ``I
want a bipartisan policy on Cyprus.''
   ``I have had a very fruitful and intensive visit to
Washington,'' he told reporters about his four day days of talks
with President Reagan, Bush, Dukakis and other U.S. officials.
   Vassiliou said he expected the Reagan administration to work for
a solution in its remaining months in office _ ``there is no reason
why we should lose time because of the elections.''
   He said he found strong U.S. support for his Aug. 24 talks in
New York with Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash under the
auspices of U.N. Secretary General Javier Perez de Cuellar.
