<2ND_LINE>AM-Tax Bill, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0711,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Minor Tax Changes Would Help Various Groups</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS one graf after 5th graf bgng ``The chief ... '' to
explain changes.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House on Thursday gave lopsided bipartisan
approval to a $7.1 billion election-year package of minor tax
changes that would benefit farmers, mutual-fund owners, free-lance
writers and rural mail carriers.
   The targeted tax cuts would be financed by higher taxes on
defense contractors, certain other corporations, pipe smokers and
purchasers of single-premium life insurance policies.
   The 380-25 vote for the bill was easily the widest margin by
which any tax legislation has been approved over the last decade.
Voting for the measure were 230 Democrats and 150 Republicans; 6
Democrats and 19 Republicans voted no.
   The bill now goes to the Senate, where the Finance Committee has
approved a stripped-down version.
   The chief purpose of the 960-page House bill is to correct
errors and clear up ambiguities in the landmark tax overhaul enaced
in 1986. Since this is almost certainly the only tax bill with a
chance of becoming law this year, the Ways and Means Committee used
it to carry dozens of substantive tax changes.
   Despite its size, the bill is one of the smallest pieces of tax
legislation in recent years. The Joint Committee on Taxation
estimates it would cut taxes by about $7.1 billion through 1991 and
raise taxes by about $47 million less than that amount.
   Nevertheless, Rep. Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill., committee chairman,
told the House, ``This bill is in keeping with the spirit of tax
reform.''
   He and Rep. Bill Archer of Texas, senior Republican on the
committee, emphasized that unlike most tax bills of recent years,
the legislation includes no tax breaks that are targeted for the
benefit of only one or two individuals or corporations.
   Among the dozens of provisions are those to:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   _Wipe out a 1987 requirement that farmers, construction
companies and other tax-exempt off-road users of diesel fuel pay
the federal tax of 15.1 cents a gallon and later apply for a
refund. Farmers especially have objected to the loss of cash flow
and paperwork.
   _Permanently permit owners of mutual fund shares to deduct
certain operating expenses of the fund without regard to a general
provision allowing deduction of only miscellaneous expenses that
exceed 2 percent of income.
   _Allow a worker to avoid tax on up to $1,500 of year of
employer-provided education assistance, down from an earlier $5,250
level. Most graduate education (except for teaching or research
assistance) would not qualify.
   _Extend through 1990 a tax credit for owners of newly
constructed low-income rental housing.
   _Impose a tax of $2.67 per pound on pipe tobacco.
   _Extend through 1990 a tax exemption for bonds issued by state
and local governments to help low-income families buy their first
home.
   _Allow free-lance writers, artists and photographers to deduct
work-related expenses even before a project produces income.
Similar relief from general ``uniform capitalization'' rules would
be included for certain livestock producers (the so-called heifer
tax) and growers of pistachio nuts.
   _Allow an 80 percent deduction for contributions to college
athletic scholarship funds even when such ``gifts'' guarantee a fan
the privilege of buying a game ticket.
   _Extend through 1990 a credit under which the government pays
the first year of wages for certain newly hired economically
disadvantaged workers.
   _Repeal the completed-contract accounting method, which has
produced tax savings for defense contractors and large construction
companies.
   _Reduce from 70 percent to 50 percent the dividend-received
deduction for corporations that own less than 20 percent of the
stock in another.
   _Repeal a provision that has allowed Alaska Native corporations
to sell some of their unused tax credits to other companies.
Lawmakers say the benefit has been badly abused.
   _Remove some of the tax advantages of using single-premium life
insurance as an investment. Loans from such policies would be taxed
as cash withdrawals; the new rules would apply to policies whose
cash value builds more quickly than one paid through seven equal
annual premiums.
   _Allow rural mail carriers to deduct 33.75 cents for each mile a
personal car is driven on a mail route; most people are allowed
22.5 cents a mile for business-related mileage.
   _Permit operators of offshore or Alaska oil rigs and of some
commercial vessels (but not luxury liners) to deduct the full cost
of meals provided to employees; most business may deduct only 80
percent.
   _Allow a surviving spouse to defer taxation on certain profits
from the sale of a principal home, just as though the spouse had
not died. Present law denies such a break if a spouse dies after a
home is sold and before a new one is built.
   _Prohibit any person with a home-based business (including
moonlighters) from deducting any part of the base monthly telephone
charge as a business expense.
   _Deny Social Security benefits to deported Nazi war criminals.
   _Permit states and blood-collection facilities to require blood
donors to list their Social Security numbers so they can be traced
if tests determine their blood is carryng the AIDS virus.
   _Exempt from Social Security taxes employees from Amish and
other sects with religious objections to the program; self-employed
already are exempt.
</TEXT>
