<FILEID>AP-NR-08-05-88 0052EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a BC-Theater     08-05 0609</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Theater,0624</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Checkmates,' A New Comedy, Opens on Broadway</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No PMs planned.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Checkmates'' is a crudely constructed,
cartoonish comedy by Ron Milner about the generation gap, but this
time the gap isn't between father and son or mother and daughter.
It's a chasm between two married couples.
   These middle-class couples also happen to be black, but don't
expect any revelations about race relations and what being black in
a white society can do to a marriage. ``Checkmates,'' which opened
Thursday at the 46th Street Theater, is played mainly for laughs _
cheap laughs, easy laughs, laughs that do little to illuminate
character or advance the plot.
   Plot is something that ``Checkmates'' rarely encounters. The
play is mostly a series of sitcom sketches populated by one couple
or the other as they fight, make love or just try to get through
the day. Naturally, these people are a study in contrast.
   Frank and Mattie Cooper have been married for 45 years. They
have four children, six grandchildren and a comfortable home in
Detroit where they are getting through Frank's retirement by
talking about the couple upstairs.
   Their tenants are Sylvester and Laura Williams, young, upwardly
mobile and and preoccupied with ``self'' rather than ``we.'' He's a
salesman. She works as a buyer for a department store. Career
conflicts _ she's on the way up, he could be on the way down _
threaten their marriage.
   The audience watches as one marriage reaffirms itself and the
other falls apart. But it's hard to care for these characters
whether they are up or down.
   Milner wrote the book for ``Don't Get God Started,'' a gospel
show that ran on Broadway for several months last season. It was a
musical morality tale with dramatized lessons about life and love
interspersed with some rousing gospel songs.
   Those same messages about sharing, caring and giving show up in
``Checkmates,'' but this time there are no soaring melodies to lift
the spirits between the sagging and soggy vingettes.
   To pad out the evening, the playwright flashes back to tell the
older couple's story. You can tell when that happens because the
lighting _ some lurid effects by designer Ronald Wallace _ changes
color. In these moments, the audience learns of Frank's decision to
leave his family and fight during World War II as well as his
affair with a French woman.
   At least the production has been superbly cast, with Ruby Dee
and Paul Winfield starring as the older duo and Denzel Washington
and Marsha Jackson appearing as the younger couple.
   Miss Dee is a radiant actress and Winfield a forceful stage
presence, so they mine the comedy for every giggle they can. It's
depressing to watch them work so hard with such meager results.
   Washington has an ingratiating stage manner. He survives because
of his winning personality and not because of anything the author
gives him to say or do. Miss Jackson, as the young wife, has a
harder job. She must always be on the offensive, hammering away at
her husband or whining about her job, and the complaints grow
tiresome.
   The wide stage at the 46th Street Theater has been sliced in
half by two separate apartments, both realistically designed by
Edward Burbridge. The action alternates between the two homes with
the predictability of a boring tennis match.
   Director Woodie King, Jr., doesn't do anything to lessen the
ping-pong effect. But it's hard to see what King could have done to
liven up the evening. Because of Milner's simple-minded and obvious
script, ``Checkmates'' is checkmated even before the curtain goes
up.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
