<1ST_LINE>r a AM-JacksonThreat     08-05 0356</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson Threat,0368</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Accused Of Threatening To Kill Jesse Jackson Pleads Guilty</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LORI DODGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who said he grew up with ``prejudices
against anything that isn't white'' pleaded guilty Thursday to a
charge that he had threatened to kill black Democratic presidential
aspirant Jesse Jackson.
   Londell Williams, 30, pleaded innocent in May to four charges
contained in a federal indictment against him. He had been
scheduled to stand trial Aug. 8.
   Under a plea bargain, he pleaded guilty Thursday before U.S.
District Judge Edward Filippine to charges of threatening Jackson's
life and possessing an unregistered automatic rifle.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney David Rosen said he would move to drop
the other two charges _ threatening and intimidating a government
informant _ at sentencing, scheduled for Oct. 14.
   Williams faces up to 13 years in prison and $500,000 in fines.
   Williams and his wife, Tammy, 27, were arrested May 13 at their
apartment in Washington, Mo., about 50 miles west of St. Louis. At
the time, Jackson was campaigning for the Democratic presidential
nomination.
   The Williams were arrested after an informant told authorities
that they were involved in a conspiracy with white supremacists to
kill Jackson. The informant agreed to meet again with Williams and
wear a hidden microphone.
   The indictment did not mention conspiracy and the FBI was unable
to find any evidence that the Williamses belong to a white
supremacist organization.
   On Thursday, Rosen read part of the transcript of their recorded
conversation, in which Williams said Jackson was ``trying to make a
fool out of us white people'' by running for president.
   Williams said it was time Jackson ``goes into the refrigerator.
And that's what I'm about.'' After he was arrested, Williams told
reporters that he grew up with ``prejudices against anything that
isn't white.''
   ``There seems to be a white United States of America,'' he said.
``That's how I've been raised.''
   Mrs. Williams was indicted on charges of possessing an
unregistered automatic rifle, and threatening and intimidating the
government informant. She has pleaded innocent. Rosen said her
trial is set for Sept. 6.
</TEXT>
