<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Break-InDeath     08-05 0290</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Break-In Death,0298</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grand Jury Clears Store Owner in Shooting Death of Intruder</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Donn in 2nd graf is CQ.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KIMBERLY M. SHEARIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lobbyist for gun owners was justified
in fatally shooting an intruder who broke into his gun store two
weeks ago, a grand jury decided Thursday.
   Donn DiBiasio, 59, of Smithfield, used reasonable force in
defending himself, even though he shot the intruder more than once,
Attorney General James E. O'Neil said at a Thursday news conference.
   DiBiasio's case was turned over to the grand jury July 21, the
day after he fatally shot Wayne E. Costa, 23, three times at his
Providence store, D&B Antenna & Electronics and D-B Guns.
   He was arrested shortly after the incident and charged with
murder, then arraigned and released on $1,000 personal recognizance
the following day.
   ``It means the world has been lifted off my shoulders,'' said
DiBiasio after Thursday's announcement. ``I think this certainly
gives a message to the citizens of Rhode Island ... that the police
cannot protect all citizens at all times.''
   O'Neil denied earlier news reports that DiBiasio had appeared to
lie in wait for the intruder, since he was in the store around
10:30 p.m. when the break occurred. O'Neil said DiBiasio just
happened to be in the store.
   O'Neil said he was satisfied with the grand jury's findings and
does not think it will encourage vigilante acts.
   The grand jury heard the testimony of 13 people and police
reports and took two weeks to come up with the decision, O'Neil
said.
   DiBiasio, a Statehouse lobbyist for the Rhode Island State Rifle
and Revolver Association for 20 years, said he intends to keep his
store open.
</TEXT>
