<HEAD>Experts Examine Iranian Airbus Wreckage</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gulf-UN</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Experts from the International Civil
Aviation Organization visited the site where an Iran Air jetliner
was shot down by a U.S. warship and inspected chunks of wreckage,
Iran said Thursday.
   The report was carried by Tehran's official Islamic Republic
News Agency before the five-man ICAO team left for Dubai in the
United Arab Emirates. The Airbus A-300 was headed from Bandar Abbas
to Dubai when missiles from the USS Vincennes hit it July 3,
killing all 290 people aboard.
   IRNA said the search continued for bodies and the flight data
recorder. It said 186 bodies had been recovered.
   The ICAO, a United Nations agency based in Montreal, said the
investigators traveled on Wednesday to the area off Hengham Island
where the plane crashed into the gulf, and also examined documents
at the Bandar Abbas airport.
   American officials have said the Vincennes crew believed the
airliner was an Iranian F-14 jet fighter on an attack course. U.S.
Defense Department sources said Wednesday preliminary findings show
human error rather than malfunctioning equipment was the cause.
   The ICAO assists international civil aviation by establishing
technical standards for safety and efficiency of air navigation.
</TEXT>
