<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     08-05 0236</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0243</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Futures Prices Decline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Disappointment with the outcome of an OPEC
committee meeting and a report on U.S. oil supplies continues to
weaken oil futures prices.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the contract for September
delivery of West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S.
crude oil, fell 23 cents a barrel Thursday to close at $15.03. The
September contract had dropped sharply on Tuesday and Wednesday.
   Futures prices of refined oil products were mostly lower. The
September contract for wholesale heating oil fell 0.50 cent a
gallon to finish at 42.46 cents. Wholesale unleaded gasoline for
September slipped 0.26 cent a gallon to 44.95 cents, although most
other contract months rose.
   Analysts said prices continued to be dragged down by
disappointment that the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries' price monitoring committee ended its meeting Wednesday
in Lausanne, Switzerland without any major announcements or a call
for a full meeting of OPEC ministers.
   Another cloud hanging over the market was a report released late
Tuesday by the American Petroleum Institute on domestic oil and
gasoline supplies. Many traders had expected gasoline and oil
inventories to decline, but the API reported that stocks rose.
   ``You have problems with the (gasoline inventories); you have
problems with OPEC ... We're weak again because of that,'' said
Chris McCormack, a broker in the international energy department at
Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.
</TEXT>
