<1ST_LINE>r f PM-RetailSales Bjt   08-05 0653</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Retail Sales, Bjt,0674</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Retail Sales Continue Weak Trend In July</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Hot weather sent the nation's largest general retailers back
into a slump during July, but the stores and Wall Street analysts
are looking toward August with some optimism.
   Last month's relentless heat largely kept shoppers out of
stores, hampered retailers' attempts to clear out summer
merchandise and made sales reports issued by the stores Thursday
disappointing.
   The higher temperatures ended a modest rally the retailers
enjoyed in June.
   In addition to weather, the stores' reports reflected the
overall softness that has plagued the retail industry for about a
year and a half, said Jeffrey Feiner, an analyst with Merrill Lynch
& Co.
   Consumers have cut back on their retail spending because of high
installment debt levels and uncertainty about the economy. As a
result, retailers' sales have been a soft spot in an otherwise
strong economy.
   Consumer spending, which also includes expenditures for food,
medical care, autos, utilities, transportation and other
necessities, is watched closely because it accounts for two-thirds
of the gross national product.
   Walter Loeb, an analyst with the investment firm Morgan Stanley
& Co., said July generally is not an important month for retailers.
   But this month will be critical, especially for apparel
retailers who have been in a year-long slump as women turned away
from the retailers' offerings of shorter skirts and clothes
shoppers widely perceived as boring.
   The retailers have revamped their fall lines, and analysts
predict there will be a pickup in clothing sales that may begin
showing up in the stores' August results.
   ``I would expect sales would accelerate,'' Loeb said. ``I am
looking for a good August.''
   In their reports Thursday, several retailers recorded sales
increases under 3 percent _ meaning the stores were losing ground
to inflation, which has run at an annual rate of 4.4 percent so far
this year.
   The nation's largest retailer, Sears, Roebuck & Co., said its
overall sales rose 7.2 percent last month and 5.4 percent for the
first half of the fiscal year, compared with the same periods of
1987. Sears' sales for stores open at least a year, so-called
same-store sales, were up 2.5 percent last month and 2.1 percent
for the year so far.
   Retailers and industry analysts believe same-store sales are a
more accurate yardstick of a company's performance than figures
which include sales from new stores.
   K mart Corp. said its overall sales rose 4.8 percent last month
and 5.3 percent during the first half, while same-store sales edged
up 0.7 percent in July and 1.8 percent for the year to date.
   Wal-Mart Stores Inc. said its overall sales rose 30 percent in
July and 31 percent for the first half. Same-store sales rose 14
percent last month and 12 percent so far this year.
   J.C. Penney Co. Inc. said its overall sales rose 2.7 percent in
July and 2.6 percent for the first six months. Same-store sales
were up 2.1 percent last month and 1.6 percent in the first half.
   Dayton Hudson Corp. said its overall sales were up 13.1 percent
last month, and 17.6 percent for the year to date. The company's
same-store sales slipped 0.9 percent during July, while rising 1.5
percent over the first half.
   May Department Stores Co. said its overall sales rose 23.5
percent in July, and 12 percent over the first half. Same-stores
sales increased 4 percent for the month, and 1.2 percent so far
this year.
   F.W. Woolworth Co. reported an 11.1 percent sales gain for July,
and an 11.9 increase for the first six months.
   Montgomery Ward & Co. said its sales rose 1 percent last month,
and 2.8 percent over the first half.
   The results reported Thursday were from general merchandise and
apparel retailers. Unlike monthly retail sales figures released by
the federal government, they do not include sales at auto dealers,
supermarkets or restaurants.
</TEXT>
