<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BizWeekProbe     08-05 0459</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Biz Week Probe,0474</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Business Week Tells Its Side Of Scandal Story</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Business Week says it has not uncovered any
evidence implicating its editorial employees in a spreading scandal
involving pre-publication leaks of the magazine's stock tips, and
again has defended its actions in dealing internally with its
suspicions without telling authorities.
   The magazine in its Aug. 15 issue, released to the press late
Thursday, gave its first detailed account of the scandal, two weeks
after first confirming it was investigating the leaks.
   So far, seven people around the nation have been forced from
their jobs in connection with the magazine scandal, and federal law
enforcement officials have begun a criminal investigation.
   Evidence uncovered so far suggests some printers at two of the
four plants that print Business Week peddled unpublished copies to
brokers, who bought stocks recommended by the ``Inside Wall
Street'' column and sold them later at a profit after publication
attracted more buyers and boosted the price of the stocks.
   In the Aug. 15 issue, Business Week estimated that price changes
in 20 stocks mentioned in the column this year generated potential
profits of $2.4 million. ``Few appear to have made a killing,'' the
magazine said.
   Business Week, which is published by McGraw-Hill Inc., said its
editors detected questionable price changes in stocks mentioned in
the column as far back as early last year.
   But the magazine's editors met with McGraw-Hill lawyers, who
recommended against reporting the matter to the Securities and
Exchange Commission, Business Week said. The story said Business
Week had nothing but suspicions about stock price movements and had
no concrete evidence implicating anyone.
   While Business Week was under no legal obligation to notify the
SEC, the story said, magazine editors also were concerned that an
investigation ``might raise First Amendment problems,'' namely that
investigators might demand the names of confidential sources of
Gene Marcial, who regularly writes the column.
   Instead, the magazine attempted to ``police its own shop'' by
sharply reducing the number of Business Week copies distributed in
the McGraw-Hill building before the official release date from 600
to 20.
   The magazine also sent letters to its printers citing ``the
widespread concern about insider trading'' and reminding them of
the confidentiality policy.
   Business Week said the suspicious trading seemed to subside for
awhile, but then reappeared this past spring.
   The price moves attracted the attention of the Stock Watch
department of the New York Stock Exchange, which began its own
inquiry but did not notify Business Week or the SEC, the story said.
   The Dow Jones Professional Investor Report made the first public
disclosure of the suspicious stock movements in a story July 21,
Business Week finally confirmed its own probe and the scandal began
snowballing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
