<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Ethics-Education Bjt   08-05 0655</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ethics-Education, Bjt,0677</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Accounting Firm Helping Business Schools Expand Ethics Education</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of the world's biggest accounting firms is
spearheading a $5 million program to help smaller colleges and
universities improve their teaching of business ethics, prompted by
a survey indicating that ethics programs were ``a little spotty.''
   Chicago-based Arthur Andersen & Co. has developed PACE, a
five-year program of seminars aimed at helping faculty at business
schools nationwide to make ethics instruction part of their basic
course work.
   Duane R. Kullberg, the firm's managing partner and chief
executive officer, said Arthur Andersen views the program partly as
an investment in its own future.
   ``As one of the nation's largest employers of business school
graduates, we have a significant interest in their development,''
Kullberg said. ``This program benefits Arthur Andersen as well as
the business community in general.''
   Wall Street's insider-trading scandals and shady
defense-contract deals have focused public attention on moral
issues in business.
   But while many graduate business schools have responded by
introducing ethics courses _ often as electives for MBA candidates
_ few small colleges and public universities can match the
resources of the leading private business schools in developing
such programs.
   Harvard Business School, for example, received a $30 million
gift last year from former Securities and Exchange Commission
Chairman John S.R. Shad to finance a program in ethics education.
   But Kullberg said an Andersen-financed survey found the
development of ethics-education in the business curriculums of
smaller colleges and public universities to be ``a little spotty.''
   ``There is a desire to find a solution, a desire to find a
practical way to deal with the subject,'' he said in a telephone
interview this week.
   So Andersen developed the PACE program and invited
business-school instructors from around the nation to review it.
Some 300 of them came to the Chicago area this spring and summer at
Andersen's expense to attend two-day seminars on incorporating
ethics lessons into their routine course work.
   Andersen has asked the approximately 60 institutions that sent
representatives to this year's seminars to try the PACE approach
for at least one semester.
   The team of ethics teachers, business school instructors and
business professionals who developed PACE decided ethics should be
taught as part of the five basic business disciplines: finance,
marketing, economics, management and accounting.
   ``I see that as a big plus,'' said Conrad Doenges, a professor
of finance at the University of Texas at Austin who attended a PACE
seminar.
   In real life, Doenges said, ``ethical issues can arise at any
point at almost any time.''
   By incorporating ethics discussions into finance courses, he
said, ``the student sees ethical issues as a part of finance, as a
part of his normal business life rather than as a segmented or
compartmented area of study.''
   To foster discussions, PACE offers fictitious case studies
tailored to each discipline. The case studies are meant to reflect
ethical dilemmas that business students might face early in their
careers, such as sexual harassment, truth in advertising, plant
closings, wage discrimination and ledger manipulation.
   The dilemmas have no easy or correct solutions, but are designed
to get students talking and thinking.
   ``Students need to grapple with these issues so they can have
some experience in thinking about these issues,'' said Alison
Ashton, an assistant professor of accounting at Duke University's
Fuqua School of Business.
   Robert Allan Cooke, director of the Institute for Business
Ethics at DePaul University in Chicago and a member of the PACE
development group, said the PACE program was designed to give
business students the basic skill to deal with ethical dilemmas,
just as they learned the basic skills of management and accounting.
   ``We believe very strongly that most ethical problems that arise
come from lack of information and that lack of information results
in poor judgment,'' he said. ``We're trying to provide the
information that will help alleviate those bad judgments.''
</TEXT>
