<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Towers-SEC     08-05 0265</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Towers-SEC,0275</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Towers Financial Charged With Selling Unregistered Securities</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission on
Thursday charged Towers Financial Corp., which has made takeover
overtures for Pan American World Airways Inc., with selling $20
million in unregistered securities.
   The SEC filed a civil suit alleging that Towers failed to
satisfy disclosure requirements when it publicly sold $20 million
in notes between October 1986 and October 1987.
   Towers is a factoring firm, which buys accounts receivable at a
discount and earns a profit by collecting the full face amount.
   ``We say they financed a factoring program with an unlawful
securities offering and we want them to stop,'' said Jason
Gettinger, a staff attorney for the SEC in New York.
   The SEC asked the U.S. District Court to bar Towers from using
the money it received in the securities sales and to issue an
injunction barring the company from further violation of federal
registration requirements. The agency also said it wanted Towers to
return the noteholders' money.
   Ira L. Sorkin, who represents Towers, said the company and its
top executives recognized that ``there may be a technical violation
of the registration provisions of the Federal securities laws and
will make every effort to comply with those provisions.''
   Towers, beginning last year, made a number of announcements
indicating it might make a bid for Pan Am, but has yet to mount a
takeover and was regarded by Wall Street as a questionable suitor.
   But its overtures attracted public attention because the firm
said its offer included support from former Navy Secretary John
Lehman.
</TEXT>
