<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-LTV     08-05 0247</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-LTV,0260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>LTV Corp. Earnings Up 28 Percent In Second Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   LTV Corp., operating under Chapter 11 protection
from creditors, said Thursday its second quarter net income rose by
28.4 percent over the same period last year.
   LTV said its net income in the three months ended June 30 rose
to $157.6 million, or $1.14 per share, from $122.7 million, or 91
cents per share, a year earlier.
   A strong increase in steel sales boosted LTV's revenue to $2.1
billion, up from $1.9 billion a year earlier.
   For the six months ended June 30, LTV had net income of $321.5
million, or $2.67 per share, compared with net income of $252.3
million, or $2.17 per share, for the first six months of 1987.
   Revenue for the six months to $3.94 billion from $3.84 billion.
   ``The domestic steel industry's performance has improved as a
result of massive cost cutting, cyclical factors and a more
reasonably valued dollar,'' said Raymond H. Hay, LTV chairman and
chief executive.
   ``However, the industry continues to face the threats of
unfairly priced imported steel, and inadequate long-term return on
invested capital, as well as the risks of successfully weathering
the next economic downturn.''
   Hay emphasized a need to extend voluntary restraint agreements,
set to expire in 1898, to limit steel imports.
   LTV in May submitted a reorganization plan to creditor groups
for consideration.
   At the end of the second quarter, LTV had a negative net worth
of $1.7 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
